channel.title: Custom Cache - Re: Cache....WTF?
channel.description:
Ok First i would like to thank primadude for answering all of my last cache questions!!! i am very thankful but now i have some more. My goal by the end of the month (5 days and 2hrs) I will have a web client that downloads my own custom cache. I dont think i will have a problem with the web client part but the custom cache thing is really making my head spin. I have googled the sh!t out of this as well as looking on many other forums and i have yet to find an answer. This is pretty much what i think is correct
1. Unpack cache replace/edit models 2. Add new ints to client (for replaced/edited models) 3. Repack
It sounds really simple but i dont even know if i am right. I really REALLY need a 377 cache packer/unpacker. I have found one by Silvon but its a piece of poo and dosent work. So...
Is my dream even obtainable?
I am not one to give up but this just seems hopeless....

item.dc:creator: @TeleNubby TeleNubby
item.description:
@TeleNubby wrote:

			HashDatabase.load();
			Cache cache = getCache(0);
			com.telenubby.rs2.model.File cacheFile = cache.getFile(1);
			Archive archive = cacheFile.toArchive();
			Sprite sprite = (Sprite)archive.getArchivedFile("titlebox.dat");
			BufferedImage img = ImageIO.read(new File("test_sprite.jpeg"));
			Sprite newSprite = Sprite.createSprite(img, "titlebox.dat");
			Archive newArchive = archive
					.delete("titlebox.dat")
					.add(newSprite.getData());
			cache.update(newArchive);
	public static Sprite createSprite(BufferedImage img, String name) throws IOException
	{
		Sprite sprite = new Sprite(Unpacker.getCache(0).getFile(1).toArchive(), name);
		sprite.width = img.getWidth();
		sprite.height = img.getHeight();
		sprite.setPixels(new int[sprite.width * sprite.height]);
		sprite.setSpecialWidth(sprite.width);
		sprite.setSpecialHeight(sprite.height);
		sprite.setXOffset(0);
		sprite.setYOffset(0);
		ArrayList<Integer> palette = new ArrayList<Integer>();
		for(int x = 0; x < sprite.width; x++)
		{
			for(int y = 0; y < sprite.height; y++)
			{
				int color = img.getRGB(x, y);
				sprite.setPixel(x, y, color);
				if(!palette.contains(color))
					palette.add(color);
			}
		}
		sprite.setNumColors(palette.size());
		sprite.setPalette(convert(palette));
		return sprite;
	}
